TY  - JOUR
AU  - Hasan, Iftekhar
AU  - Marra, Miriam
AU  - Wu, Eliza
AU  - Zhang, Gaiyan
T1  - Creditor-Control Rights and the Nonsynchronicity of Global CDS Markets
PY  - 2025
Y1  - 2025/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/rcfs/cfad010
JO  - The Review of Corporate Finance Studies
JA  - Review of Corporate Finance Studies
VL  - 14
IS  - 1
SP  - 204
EP  - 260
SN  - 2046-9128
AB  - We analyze how creditor rights affect the nonsynchronicity of global corporate credit default swap spreads (CDS-NS). CDS-NS is negatively related to the country-level creditor-control rights, especially to the “restrictions on reorganization” component, where creditor-shareholder conflicts are high. The effect is concentrated in firms with high investment intensity, asset growth, information opacity, and risk. Pro-creditor bankruptcy reforms led to a decline in CDS-NS, indicating lower firm-specific idiosyncratic information being priced in credit markets. A strategic-disclosure incentive among debtors avoiding creditor intervention seems more dominant than the disciplining effect, suggesting how strengthening creditor rights affects power rebalancing between creditors and shareholders. (JEL G14, G15, G33, G34)
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rcfs/cfad010
ER  - 




